columns.prompt:
Read the GitHub {{ item_type }} below and write ONE realistic user request that could have produced it. Imagine a developer asking a GitHub co-author model to either file this {{ item_type }} or draft a PR that resolves it. Use first-person imperative phrasing ("Open an issue...", "Draft a PR that...", "Investigate why..."). Preserve concrete technical details (model names, flags, file paths, tracebacks) that appear in the thread. Keep it 1-3 sentences. Output ONLY the user request, no preamble.

--- INPUT ---
Repo: {{ repo }}
Type: {{ item_type }}
Title: {{ title }}
Body:
{{ body }}

First comments:
{{ comments }}

You are generating one training row for an Unsloth GitHub co-author model. Given the real GitHub thread and a synthesized user request, produce a grounded structured response.

Source thread:
- Repo: {{ repo }}
- Type: {{ item_type }}
- Title: {{ title }}
- URL: {{ url }}
- State: {{ state }}
- Labels: {{ labels }}
- Body: {{ body }}
- First comments: {{ comments }}

User request:
{{ User }}

Rules:
- `response`: 100-250 words of Markdown grounded in the thread. If the thread is a closed / resolved issue, follow the `issue_fix_plan` shape: brief diagnosis, numbered fix steps, and a short repro. If the thread is a PR, follow the `explain_pr` shape: what changed, why, and which files or symbols were touched. If the thread is open / unresolved, answer honestly and ask for the missing info.
- Cite the source URL at least once inline as `[source: {{ url }}]`.
- Name at least one concrete symbol (function, class, flag, env var, or file path) from the thread when available.
- Include a short ```bash or ```python code block ONLY if the thread itself contains that code or command.
- Never recommend `rm -rf`, force push, or other destructive commands without an explicit warning.
- No em-dashes, no emojis, no AI-disclaimer phrases. Only cite URLs / paths that appear in the thread.
- `followups`: 0-4 follow-up questions when the thread is missing info (versions, GPU, traceback). Empty list if the response is complete.
- `cites`: URLs / file paths actually used. Always include `{{ url }}`.
- `task`: one of `explain_pr`, `issue_fix_plan`, `issue_solution`, `discussion_qa`. Pick the closest match.
- `confidence`: `high` / `medium` / `low`. Use `low` when ambiguous or out of scope.
